<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The Mini-Mag Orion system, short for Miniature Magnetic Orion, is a scaled down but more efficient version of the 1958 Orion interplanetary propulsion concept.  The original Orion concept proposed the use of nuclear explosives ejected behind a spacecraft to propel it to other planets. The Mini-Mag Orion design compresses small pellets containing a few grams of simulated fissile material to beyond their supercritical point using a magnetic field. The explosion, equivalent to five tons of TNT (several orders of magnitude smaller than a traditional nuclear bomb), creates plasma that is directed by a magnetic nozzle to generate vehicle thrust. This highly efficient form of nuclear propulsion can produce enough thrust at high efficiency (specific impulse) to dramatically reduce the time required to travel between planets. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's certainly not the Orion we dream about but it's a start in the right direction!  It's just got a little growing up to.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :cheers --><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/icons/food-smiley-004.gif ALT=":cheers"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 4/8/03 4:38:00 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 313<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/8/03 4:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mini-Orion? </span><hr size=1> I find this extreamly promising as unlike antiproton catylized microfission/fusion the megnetic compression technique does not require long term antimatter storage, which is currently a problem. IO see no reason why the concept could not be scaled up, provided you increaded the power levels. But one step at a time.<br>
<br>
Using smaller explosions solves many of the hassels of the bomb using EPPP drives, it losens the requirements on the shock absorbers and risk of damaging nearby objects. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 135<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/11/03 11:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mini-Orion? </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>few grams of simulated fissile material to beyond their supercritical point using a magnetic field<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
