 sneak through the treaties. The spirit of the treaties was to keep nuclear weapons and large explosions out of LEO, small externaly initiated reactions behind a spacecraft won't seem like weapons to rational people. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 418<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/21/03 5:47 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=322.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mini-Orion?  </span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; a number of nutcases with an anti-nuclear agenda will try to equivocate the thing with nuclear bombs</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Remember Gagnon: No nuclear power of any sort in space. Period.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; The spirit of the treaties was to keep nuclear weapons and large explosions out of LEO, small externaly initiated reactions behind a spacecraft won't seem like weapons to rational people.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Extremists will try to make enough noise to drown out rational discussion. They'll try to claim adherence to the treaties, but their real purposes are always extremist. Certainly, anything which approaches criticality from any angle will set off alarms to these people. An RTG powered probe is equated morally &amp; politically to a bunker-buster to them.<br>
<br>
Ultimately the treaties don't mean anything because they are meant to be broken: the purpose of a treaty is for any signatory to be able to pull out or modify it at any time of their choosing in the future. At the time the treaty is negotiated, it's worthwhile for them to sign it and give it lip-service. In the future, it won't be worth it to them, they'll have some other purpose and the treaty gets in the way.<br>
